ursued by Kirchner and Fernández. Mendoza shows how Andean Patagonian communities have responded to the challenges of community-based conservation, the fashioning of wilderness zones, and the drive to create place-based monopolies that allow ecotourism destinations to compete in the global consumer economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCapitalismxEnvironmental aspectszArgentina. 0aEcotourismxEconomic aspectszArgentina. 0aEcotourismzPatagonia (Argentina and Chile). 0aNature conservationxEconomic aspectszArgentina. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aPatagonia, Argentina, adventure, trekking, ecotourism, conservation, politics, green economy, Kirchner-Fernandez, national park, environment, environmental politics, anthropology, ecology, capitalism, globalization, Latin America, New Left, Los Glaciares National Park, El Chalten, Andean Patagonian.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066608340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813596785zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813596785423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813596785.jpg  a978-3-11-066608-3  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK